  <brief_title>Pilot Study of Diet and Behavior in Children With Autism</brief_title>
  <official_title>PILOT STUDY: The Physiological Basis for Dietary Protein Intolerance in Children With Autism</official_title>
  <sponsors>
    <lead_sponsor>
      <agency>The University of Texas Health Science Center, Houston</agency>
      <agency_class>Other</agency_class>
    </lead_sponsor>
  </sponsors>
  <source>The University of Texas Health Science Center, Houston</source>
  <oversight_info>
    <has_dmc>Yes</has_dmc>
  </oversight_info>
  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      We hypothesize that in children with autism dietary antigens can change the intestine, making
      it &quot;leaky&quot; and then affecting the brain changing their behavior.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
  <detailed_description>
    <textblock>
      Subjects in 2 different diets (gluten/dairy and placebo) will be monitored for changes in
      intestinal permeability (urine lactulose mannitol ratio) and behavior (psychometric testing).
    </textblock>
  </detailed_description>
